===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} – a person ({{zh-l|*大}}) wearing a headdress (now written {{zh-l|*羊}}) of feathers or ram's horn.

The modern form could be considered an {{Han compound|羊|t1=ram or feathers|大|t2=person|ls=ic|nocap=y}}.

See also {{zh-l|*敖}}, {{zh-l|*冒}}, and {{zh-l|*免}}.

===Etymology===
From {{der|zh|sit-pro|*m(r)əj||beautiful, well, perfectly}} (STEDT, under PTB *mway).

According to {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}}, cognate with {{cog|lus|mawi||beautiful, lovely}}, {{cog|kac|moi ||perfectly, beautifully}} as well as {{cog|mjw|me-||be good}} and {{cog|kac|cha mai||good}}; the former two items from *'''moy''' "beautiful" and the latter from *'''may''' "good, well", which were two roots reconstructed separately by {{zh-ref|Benedict (1972)}}.

