===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|み|y=goon}}
From {{der|ja|ltc|-}} {{ltc-l|美}}.

The use of this character as a suffix in given names is an [[ateji]] ({{m|ja|当て字}}) for the native Japanese syllable {{m|ja|み|tr=mi}}, capitalizing on the character’s meaning of “beauty”. Morphologically, this {{m|ja|み|tr=mi}} typically stems from one of three sources:
* The Old Japanese feminine suffix {{m|ja|み|tr=‐mi}}.
* The nominalizing suffix {{m|ja|み|tr=‐mi}} attached to adjective stems (such as {{m|ja|宏|tr=hiro‐|t=broad}} in {{m|ja|宏美|tr=Hiromi}}).
* The continuative form ({{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren’yōkei}}) of verbs ending in {{m|ja|む|tr=‐mu}} (such as {{m|ja|恵む|tr=megumu|t=to bless}} becoming the noun {{m|ja|恵み|tr=megumi|t=blessing}} in {{m|ja|恵美|tr=Megumi}}).

====Pronunciation====
{{ja-pron|み|acc_ref=NKD2}}
* As a given name suffix, the pitch accent of the resulting compound generally depends on the mora count and the lexical derivation of the name:
** Bimoraic names (such as {{m|ja|恵美|tr=Emi}}) typically take an ''atamadaka'' (head‐high) pitch accent, which also aligns with the accentuation of underlying native nouns like {{m|ja|笑み|tr=emi|t=smile}}.
** Trimoraic names strongly tend to take a ''heiban'' (flat) pitch accent. This aligns with standard prosodic patterns for three‐mora names ending in this suffix, as well as derivations from deverbal nouns (such as {{m|ja|恵み|tr=megumi|t=blessing}}) or nominalized adjectives (such as {{m|ja|広み|tr=hiromi|t=broadness}}).

